{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656804"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:18:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:18:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18765"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18765"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0,0.9,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77404"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11497"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62911"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5373"},{"type":"tags","id":"10201"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"},{"type":"tags","id":"10207"},{"type":"tags","id":"10215"},{"type":"tags","id":"10217"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77404"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman who regularly plays tennis presents for a bone density scan. The scan shows increased bone mineral density in her dominant arm compared to her non-dominant arm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the physiological principle explaining this finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone strength relates to genetic factors","Bone growth occurs symmetrically","Bone formation depends on calcium intake","Bone remodels in response to mechanical stress","Bone density increases with blood flow"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone remodels in response to mechanical stress\u003C/strong\u003E. This principle, known as Wolff\u0027s law, describes how bone tissue adapts its structure according to the mechanical forces placed upon it. In tennis players, the repeated loading of the dominant arm leads to increased bone formation through enhanced osteoblast activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone density increases with blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E - While blood flow is important for bone health, it is not the primary driver of adaptive bone remodelling\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone growth occurs symmetrically\u003C/strong\u003E - Bone adapts specifically to localised mechanical forces, leading to asymmetric changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone formation depends on calcium intake\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcium is necessary for bone formation, it does not determine the pattern of bone remodelling\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone strength relates to genetic factors\u003C/strong\u003E - Though genetics influence bone characteristics, mechanical loading is the key factor in adaptive remodelling\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis process involves both osteoblasts and osteoclasts working in concert to reshape the bone architecture to better withstand the specific mechanical stresses placed upon it.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wolff\u0027s law states that bone adapts to mechanical loading by remodelling to become stronger in response to stress.","Osteoblasts and osteoclasts work together to reshape bone according to mechanical forces.","Physical loading stimulates bone formation while lack of loading leads to bone loss."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019.","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18765"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62911"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T22:08:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T22:09:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11497"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77404"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"c